<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s computer business and its Unix operating system got a big boost Friday when the company won an estimated $929 million Air Force contract. 

   The award provides AT&amp;T with much-needed credibility in the computer industry, analysts said, and is likely to be used by the telephone giant as a major marketing tool. 
AT&amp;T executives said the contract with options runs for eight years and could be worth more than $4.5 billion if the Defense Department and civilian agencies order their authorized limits for equipment, software and services. 

   The Air Force contract, one of the government's largest computer orders ever, had been closely watched by the computer industry. 
The size of the contract helped create a major industry fight over future computer standards, because the Air Force required bidders to offer systems compatible with Unix, an operating system developed and licensed by AT&amp;T that has become increasingly popular as the base level of software controlling operations on engineering workstations, many minicomputers and some personal computers. 

   Digital Equipment Corp. and Wang Laboratories Inc., for instance, didn't bid after protesting against the Air Force's requirement of compatibility with AT&amp;T's latest version of Unix-Unix System V. 

   Robert Kavner, president of AT&amp;T's Data Systems Group, said he hopes the contract will help AT&amp;T reach an agreement with the Open Software Foundation, a computer group challenging the company's control of Unix. 
The group has pledged to develop a system using International Business Machines Corp.'s Unix version, AIX, which isn't fully compatible with Unix System V. AT&amp;T, in turn, has formed a group to push Unix System V. 

   "This bid doesn't decide the entire marketplace," Mr. Kavner said. 
"But it is an incremental affirmation of our operating system. 
I hope those in OSF will continue to ship Unix System V and feel more and more comfortable it's the route to go." 

   How much business AT&amp;T actually will get from the contract isn't clear. 
Capt. Warren Sypher, a spokesman for the Air Force Communications Command, which announced the contract, said he understood its value to be $929 million over eight years. 
However, AT&amp;T executives said that the Pentagon agencies covered by the contract are authorized to spend about $4.5 billion, and that the $929 million estimate covers only the first two years. 

   Whatever its final value, the win gives AT&amp;T's computer business a shot in the arm. 
AT&amp;T's current computer revenue is about $1 billion annually, analysts estimate, and the unit, which has had losses totaling billions of dollars, isn't expected to become profitable until late next year at the earliest. 

   "They certainly need whatever they can get" in computer orders, said Richard Toole of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. 
"But I really think their problems in computers will have to be solved by acquisition." 
Mr. Kavner said the contract will help AT&amp;T's Data Systems Group turn profitable sooner than his budget now plans. 

   Air Force officials said IBM, Planning Research Corp., Honeywell Inc., Lockheed Corp. and Zenith Electronics Corp. also bid on the contract. 
One Air Force spokesman said bidding was so competitive that prices were cut by 70%; the Air Force originally estimated its initial purchases would cost $3.5 billion, the spokesman said. 

   An IBM spokesman said the computer giant is disappointed it didn't win. 
"We are going to ask the Air Force for a debriefing to understand why," the spokesman said. 
Any protests would be filed with the General Services Administration, Air Force officials said. 

   Warren G. Corgan, vice president of AT&amp;T's Federal Systems Division, said the contract operates as a catalog, with AT&amp;T supplying a list of about 250 items, including AT&amp;T's 3B2/600 minicomputers, software, maintenance, systems integration and other work. 

   Defense Department agencies will buy the estimated $929 million of gear in the first two years, but can continue buying hardware for an additional three years and maintenance for an additional six years, Mr. Corgan said. 
AT&amp;T has been asked to ship the first 16 minicomputers to the Air Force by Jan. 3, he said. 
The agencies may buy as many as 20,000 AT&amp;T minicomputers, according to AT&amp;T. 

   Meanwhile, Mr. Corgan said, civilian agencies can select items from the catalog after the first year of the contract. 
He estimated that buying by civilian agencies could boost purchases by 10% to 20% above the $4.6 billion of authorized spending by Defense Department agencies. 

   AT&amp;T executives said about 60% of the revenue from the contract will be for AT&amp;T items, which it will start shipping in volume in next year's second quarter. 
AT&amp;T also will supply the government with gear and services from other companies. 
Control Data Corp., for instance, will supply magnetic disk drives, and TRW Inc. will supply engineering and networks linking computers. 

   AT&amp;T last won a major government computer contract three years ago, when it beat IBM for a three-year contract from the National Security Agency with an estimated value at the time of $946 million. 
"This contract dwarfs the NSA contract," Mr. Corgan said. 

   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading Friday, AT&amp;T shares rose 75 cents to close at $28. 

</TEXT>
