<HEAD>Princess Anne Denies Reports She's to Divorce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Anne, separated from her husband since
August, on Monday denied reports in British newspapers that she is
to divorce Capt. Mark Phillips.
   ``Divorce? It's not been mentioned,'' Queen Elizabeth II's only
daughter told reporters outside her Gatcombe Park home, British
Broadcasting Corp. television reported.
   Buckingham Palace refused to comment on the Monday reports in
the Daily Express, Daily Mail and Daily Mirror newspapers.
   Anne, 39, and Phillips, 41, separated last August after 15 years
of marriage. They have two children.
   A spokesman at Buckingham Palace, who was not identified in
keeping with British custom, said: ``I have nothing to add to what
was said at the time of the separation.''
   The palace issued a statement on Aug. 31 that said: ``Her Royal
Highness, the Princess Royal, and Captain Mark Phillips have
decided to separate on terms agreed between them. There are no
plans for divorce proceedings.''
   At the time, royal sources said the queen was ``obviously
saddened'' but understood the couple's decision.
   Princess Margaret, Queen Elizabeth II's younger sister, was
divorced from her husband, Lord Snowdon, in 1978.
</TEXT>
